      "symbolism": "Wyrd symbolizes the inescapable consequences of actions and the interconnected nature of reality. The image of weaving represents how individual threads (lives) create a larger pattern (collective fate). The Norns' presence at Yggdrasil's base shows that fate is foundational to existence. That even Odin is subject to wyrd demonstrates that cosmic law transcends even divine will. Wyrd teaches acceptance of consequences while maintaining agency in how one responds to circumstances. The concept emphasizes that past, present, and future are interconnected‚Äîwhat was shapes what is, which shapes what will be.",
      "culturalSignificance": "Wyrd profoundly influenced Norse culture, creating an emphasis on reputation and honor that would outlast death. If fate was inescapable, what mattered was how you faced it‚Äîcourage in the face of wyrd brought eternal glory. The concept supported warrior culture where brave death was preferable to shameful survival. Wyrd shaped Norse literature, where heroes often know their doom yet choose to meet it nobly. Modern Norse paganism uses wyrd in understanding consequences and personal responsibility. The Anglo-Saxon 'wyrd' evolved into modern English 'weird,' originally meaning 'fate.'"
